WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:08.840
[Amit Varma]: Assuming that being alive is a good thing, we are all lucky to have been born in these

00:00:08.840 --> 00:00:09.840
[Amit Varma]: times.

00:00:09.840 --> 00:00:15.080
[Amit Varma]: As recently as 200 years ago, I'd have expected to be dead before 40, leave alone reach this

00:00:15.080 --> 00:00:16.800
[Amit Varma]: ripe old age of 47.

00:00:16.800 --> 00:00:20.880
[Amit Varma]: If I got a common cold or an allergy, I could just die of that.

00:00:20.880 --> 00:00:24.320
[Amit Varma]: Forget about diseases like cancer because most people didn't live long enough to get

00:00:24.320 --> 00:00:25.320
[Amit Varma]: it.

00:00:25.320 --> 00:00:29.080
[Amit Varma]: In the 19th century, alternative medicine, which I'd call quackery, thrived because

00:00:29.080 --> 00:00:31.280
[Amit Varma]: mainstream medicine was a mess.

00:00:31.280 --> 00:00:36.320
[Amit Varma]: The germ theory wasn't yet accepted by the profession and just going to a hospital could

00:00:36.320 --> 00:00:38.720
[Amit Varma]: kill you, even if disease didn't.

00:00:38.720 --> 00:00:40.400
[Amit Varma]: Even basic hygiene was absent.

00:00:40.400 --> 00:00:44.620
[Amit Varma]: One of my heroes, Mary Wollstonecraft, died after giving birth to her daughter, who we

00:00:44.620 --> 00:00:48.920
[Amit Varma]: now remember as Mary Shelley, because a doctor hadn't washed his hands.

00:00:48.920 --> 00:00:49.920
[Amit Varma]: She got a fatal infection.

00:00:49.920 --> 00:00:51.720
[Amit Varma]: Well, times have changed.

00:00:51.720 --> 00:00:56.440
[Amit Varma]: The medicine of today would seem like unbelievable magic to the primitives of just a hundred

00:00:56.440 --> 00:00:57.480
[Amit Varma]: years ago.

00:00:57.480 --> 00:00:59.160
[Amit Varma]: But it's not magic, it's science.

00:00:59.160 --> 00:01:02.160
[Amit Varma]: Now here's the thing, we should still not be complacent.

00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:06.640
[Amit Varma]: Our scientists might have understood our bodies and created magnificent medicines, but those

00:01:06.640 --> 00:01:08.800
[Amit Varma]: medicines still have to reach us.

00:01:08.800 --> 00:01:10.220
[Amit Varma]: Someone has to make them.

00:01:10.220 --> 00:01:13.960
[Amit Varma]: You can create the finest of medicines in your labs, but how are they actually being

00:01:13.960 --> 00:01:16.040
[Amit Varma]: manufactured in our factories?

00:01:16.040 --> 00:01:18.040
[Amit Varma]: Is there Jugaar involved?

00:01:18.040 --> 00:01:20.200
[Amit Varma]: Are people dying as a result?

00:01:20.200 --> 00:01:26.920
[Amit Varma]: The answer, especially if you are in India, is yes.

00:01:26.920 --> 00:01:32.480
[Unknown]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen, our weekly podcast on economics, politics and behavioural

00:01:32.480 --> 00:01:33.480
[Unknown]: science.

00:01:33.480 --> 00:01:39.520
[Amit Varma]: Please welcome your host, Amit Verma.

00:01:39.520 --> 00:01:40.880
[Amit Varma]: Welcome to The Seen and the Unseen.

00:01:40.880 --> 00:01:46.320
[Amit Varma]: My guest today is Dinesh Thakur, once a respected scientist in the healthcare industry and now

00:01:46.320 --> 00:01:49.280
[Amit Varma]: a crusader on behalf of all of us.

00:01:49.280 --> 00:01:54.480
[Amit Varma]: I first read about Dinesh in a brilliant book by Catherine Eban called Bottle of Lies, Ranbaxy

00:01:54.480 --> 00:01:57.000
[Amit Varma]: and the Dark Side of Indian Pharma.

00:01:57.000 --> 00:02:00.760
[Amit Varma]: Dinesh is one of the heroes of the book, which is about the great fraud committed by the

00:02:00.760 --> 00:02:05.480
[Amit Varma]: company Ranbaxy, which no doubt took countless lives across the world.

00:02:05.480 --> 00:02:07.240
[Amit Varma]: Now some quick context.

00:02:07.240 --> 00:02:11.000
[Amit Varma]: In the pharma world, big companies spend huge amounts of money creating new drugs.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:16.000
[Amit Varma]: When a new drug created by a company gets approved by regulators, they have the exclusive

00:02:16.000 --> 00:02:18.600
[Amit Varma]: right to make it and sell it for a number of years.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:22.120
[Amit Varma]: This allows them to recoup the expenses of research and development.

00:02:22.120 --> 00:02:27.400
[Amit Varma]: Now after this period expires, other companies can also make these medicines and these are

00:02:27.400 --> 00:02:29.000
[Amit Varma]: now called generics.

00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:33.400
[Amit Varma]: These generics are sold at a much lower cost than the original drug.

00:02:33.400 --> 00:02:36.840
[Amit Varma]: And if you want to make something for a low cost, well, India is a good place to start.

00:02:36.840 --> 00:02:41.720
[Amit Varma]: The Indian pharma industry's reputation got a big boost about a couple of decades ago

00:02:41.720 --> 00:02:47.040
[Amit Varma]: when Cipla, driven by the visionary Yusuf Hameed, made cocktails of AIDS medicine for

00:02:47.040 --> 00:02:51.440
[Amit Varma]: a dollar a day, which was a fraction of what it had cost until then.

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:56.400
[Amit Varma]: This was a big deal for the developing world, especially Africa, and probably saved millions

00:02:56.400 --> 00:02:57.400
[Amit Varma]: of lives.

00:02:57.400 --> 00:03:01.960
[Amit Varma]: The remarkable thing about this was that the reduction in cost did not mean a reduction

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:02.960
[Amit Varma]: in quality.

00:03:02.960 --> 00:03:07.520
[Amit Varma]: Cipla's processes were outstanding and they helped get India the reputation of being the

00:03:07.520 --> 00:03:08.960
[Amit Varma]: pharmacy of the world.

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:14.820
[Amit Varma]: Now Indian companies rushed in to make generics and one of the early giants was Ranbaxy.

00:03:14.820 --> 00:03:17.200
[Amit Varma]: This is the part of the story where Dinesh comes in.

00:03:17.200 --> 00:03:22.720
[Amit Varma]: He left a plush job in the USA to come work at Ranbaxy, excited by this new age of Indian

00:03:22.720 --> 00:03:23.720
[Amit Varma]: pharma.

00:03:23.720 --> 00:03:28.560
[Amit Varma]: But he soon realised that Ranbaxy was a company driven by Jugaad.

00:03:28.560 --> 00:03:33.380
[Amit Varma]: While on the job, he found out that they routinely forge data to give to regulators.

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:36.320
[Amit Varma]: Most of their so-called medicines were never even tested.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:41.640
[Amit Varma]: Dinesh and his team found that over 50% of the data given by Ranbaxy to the FDA, the

00:03:41.640 --> 00:03:44.240
[Amit Varma]: main regulator in the USA, was fake.

00:03:44.240 --> 00:03:46.880
[Amit Varma]: 100% of the data for India was fake.

00:03:46.880 --> 00:03:47.880
[Amit Varma]: All of it.

00:03:47.880 --> 00:03:49.560
[Amit Varma]: And ditto for the developing world.

00:03:49.560 --> 00:03:54.040
[Amit Varma]: In fact, in an internal meeting, the subject came up that the medicine Ranbaxy sent to

00:03:54.040 --> 00:03:56.860
[Amit Varma]: Africa probably did not work.

00:03:56.860 --> 00:04:02.760
[Amit Varma]: One Ranbaxy executive replied, quote, who cares, it's just blacks dying, stop quote.

00:04:02.760 --> 00:04:05.800
[Amit Varma]: When Dinesh realised what was happening, he resigned.

00:04:05.800 --> 00:04:10.300
[Amit Varma]: And then he realised that he could not stay silent while millions of people were putting

00:04:10.300 --> 00:04:12.960
[Amit Varma]: their faith in medicines that could kill them.

00:04:12.960 --> 00:04:17.000
[Amit Varma]: So he complained to the FDA, who began an inquiry into Ranbaxy.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:20.100
[Amit Varma]: They filed a suit against Ranbaxy and Ranbaxy lost.

00:04:20.100 --> 00:04:25.160
[Amit Varma]: They paid out a huge sum as a settlement and admitted that they were guilty of all that

00:04:25.160 --> 00:04:26.820
[Amit Varma]: they had been accused of.

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:28.800
[Amit Varma]: But this did not solve anything in India.

00:04:28.800 --> 00:04:33.120
[Amit Varma]: The culture of Jugaad continues in the Indian pharma industry to this day.

00:04:33.120 --> 00:04:38.320
[Amit Varma]: In his conversation with me, Dinesh describes in chilling detail not only his own experiences

00:04:38.320 --> 00:04:44.680
[Amit Varma]: at Ranbaxy, but also the state of Indian pharma since and why he continues to wage a crusade

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:45.840
[Amit Varma]: to reform the system.

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:50.480
[Amit Varma]: Now, I know I've spent a lot of time on this introduction giving this context, but I did

00:04:50.480 --> 00:04:55.560
